To solve the given system of linear equations using block matrices, we first write the system in matrix form:

$$
\begin{bmatrix}
2 & 1 & 3 \\
4 & 2 & 6 \\
3 & 1 & 4
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
x \\
y \\
z
\end{bmatrix} =
\begin{bmatrix}
11 \\
22 \\
16
\end{bmatrix}
$$

Now, let's partition the coefficient matrix into block matrices:

$$
\begin{bmatrix}
A_{11} & A_{12} \\
A_{21} & A_{22}
\end{bmatrix} =
\begin{bmatrix}
2 & 1 \\
4 & 2
\end{bmatrix}
\oplus
\begin{bmatrix}
3 \\
6
\end{bmatrix}
\oplus
\begin{bmatrix}
3 \\
4
\end{bmatrix}
$$

Here, $A_{11} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 & 1 \\ 4 & 2 \end{bmatrix}$, $A_{12} = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 6 \end{bmatrix}$, $A_{21} = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix}$, and $A_{22} = 0$ (since there is no 2x2 block matrix in the lower right corner).

Now, we can rewrite the system of linear equations using block matrices:

$$
\begin{bmatrix}
A_{11} & A_{12} \\
A_{21} & A_{22}
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
x \\
y \\
z
\end{bmatrix} =
\begin{bmatrix}
11 \\
22 \\
16
\end{bmatrix}
$$

$$
\begin{bmatrix}
A_{11} & A_{12} \\
A_{21} & A_{22}
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
x \\
\begin{bmatrix}
y \\
z
\end{bmatrix}
\end{bmatrix} =
\begin{bmatrix}
11 \\
\begin{bmatrix}
22 \\
16
\end{bmatrix}
\end{bmatrix}
$$

Now, we can solve the block matrix system:

1. Solve $A_{11}x + A_{12}\begin{bmatrix} y \\ z \end{bmatrix} = 11$ for $x$:

$$
\begin{bmatrix}
2 & 1 \\
4 & 2
\end{bmatrix}x +
\begin{bmatrix}
3 \\
6
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
y \\
z
\end{bmatrix} = 11
$$

$$
\begin{bmatrix}
2 & 1 \\
4 & 2
\end{bmatrix}x =
11 - 3y - 6z
$$

Since $A_{11}$ is a 2x2 matrix, we can solve for $x$ using the inverse of $A_{11}$:

$$
x = A_{11}^{-1}(11 - 3y - 6z)
$$

2. Solve $A_{21}x + A_{22}\begin{bmatrix} y \\ z \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 22 \\ 16 \end{bmatrix}$ for $\begin{bmatrix} y \\ z \end{bmatrix}$:

$$
\begin{bmatrix}
3 \\
4
\end{bmatrix}x = \begin{bmatrix} 22 \\ 16 \end{bmatrix}
$$

Substitute the expression for $x$ from step 1:

$$
\begin{bmatrix}
3 \\
4
\end{bmatrix}A_{11}^{-1}(11 - 3y - 6z) = \begin{bmatrix} 22 \\ 16 \end{bmatrix}
$$

Now, we can solve for $\begin{bmatrix} y \\ z \end{bmatrix}$:

$$
\begin{bmatrix}
3 \\
4
\end{bmatrix}A_{11}^{-1}(11 - 3y - 6z) = \begin{bmatrix} 22 \\ 16 \end{bmatrix}
$$

However, we can see that the second equation is just a multiple of the first equation (4x + 2y + 6z = 2(2x + y + 3z)). This means that the system of linear equations is dependent, and there is no unique solution for $(x, y, z)$. Instead, the solution will be a family of solutions depending on a free variable.
